items.text: This release doesn't have as many flashy new features as the previous release, 0.6, but internally it's an even bigger release. The client side code has been cleaned up and refactored, which provides a much better base for tackling some of the [major features](https://github.com/urbanairship/tessera/labels/major-feature) in future releases.

The big news is that the client-side JavaScript code has been
re-written in Microsoft's
[TypeScript](http://www.typescriptlang.org/). TypeScript is a
superset of the ECMAScript 6 specification with optional type
annotations, which compiles down to JavaScript.

As part of the refactoring, the homegrown object model library
has been replaced with standard JavaScript classes, using
ECMAScript 6's `class` syntax. This makes the hierarchy of
dashboard items much easier to extend.

Along with the re-write, the build workflow has been updated to
use Browserify and Babel.js, with more components being loaded
from [npm](https://www.npmjs.com/) rather than being checked in
to the project.

Property editing has generally been tightened up in small ways. Boolean values are rendered with a `select` dropdown, and will reliably show the current value. Constrained numeric fields related to the grid, such as cell `span` and `offset` are also rendered with a select now, so it's impossible to enter invalid values.

* Dashboards can now be marked as favorites, and accessed from the [favorites](/favorites) page. Look for the star icon in dashboard lists and the dashboard toolbar. They're stored in your browser's `localStorage`. * Don't display tags with zero dashboards in the tag list. * Don't allow saving dashboards when a transform has been applied. * A UI for import and export of dashboards from local JSON files. * HandlebarsJS engine upgraded to version 3.0. * See the [full list of closed issues](https://github.com/urbanairship/tessera/issues?q=milestone%3A%22Release+0.7%22+is%3Aclosed)

### Timer Stats

A timer stat presentation is very similar to a singlestat, but shows one of the summation values translated to a human-readable time span.

### Timeshift Single Stats

Like timeshift summation tables, this presentation takes the
query and compares it to the same query shifted back in time. The
delta can be displayed as a raw value or a percentage.

### Comparison Singlestats

Just like timeshift singlestats, just comparing two arbitrary queries.

### Override Chart Renderer

The chart renderer can now be set on a per-chart basis,
overriding the default.

Now if there’s something you need to do with a graphite query
that flot charts don’t support, you can selectively use
graphite’s PNG renderer.
